{"title_page": "Drug harmfulness", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Soft drug|meanings pertaining to the metabolism of drugs|retrometabolic drug design}}\n{{Disputed|date=November 2015}}\n[[File:Drug danger and dependence.svg|alt=|thumb|The diagram shows the dependence potential and the relation between active and lethal dose of some psychoactive substances]]\n'''Drug harmfulness''' is the degree to which a [[psychoactive drug]] is harmful to a user and is measured in various ways, such as by [[Substance use disorder|addictiveness]] and the potential for physical harm. More harmful drugs are called \"hard drugs\"<ref name=hardaz>{{cite book|title=The A-Z Encyclopedia of Alcohol and Drug Abuse|author=Thomas Nordegren|year=2002|isbn=1-58112-404-X|page=327|publisher=[[Brown Walker Press]]|location=Parkland, Fla.}}</ref>, and less harmful drugs are called \"soft drugs\".<ref name=softaz>{{cite book|title=The A-Z Encyclopedia of Alcohol and Drug Abuse|author=Thomas Nordegren|year=2002|isbn=1-58112-404-X|page=597|publisher=Brown Walker Press|location=Parkland, Fla.}}</ref> The term \"soft drug\" is considered controversial by its critics as it may imply that soft drugs cause no or insignificant harm.<ref name=softaz/>\n\n== Drug policy ==\nThe distinction between soft drugs and hard drugs is important in the [[drug policy of the Netherlands]], where [[Cannabis cultivation|cannabis production]], [[Cannabis coffee shops|retail]] and use come under official tolerance, subject to certain conditions. The Dutch [[Opium Law]] contains two lists of drugs, List I and List II, that are colloquially considered to be lists of hard and soft drugs, respectively. Other countries typically have more than two categories. For example, the [[United States]] has five schedules in the [[Controlled Substances Act]], ranging from one through five. The [[United Kingdom]] has three classes in the [[Misuse of Drugs Act 1971]]: A, B and C.\n\n== Hard and soft drugs ==\nAccording to the legal system of the Netherlands; selected soft drugs are tolerated legally while other hard drugs are illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.government.nl/topics/drugs/how-does-the-law-distinguish-between-soft-and-hard-drugs|title=How does the law distinguish between soft and hard drugs? -|last=|first=|date=|website=Government of the Netherlands, Ministry of Justice and Security|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 27, 2020}}</ref> Soft drugs can be tolerated in various ways whether it be total lack of regulation or some regulation, but still legal availability to the public.\n\n=== Hard drugs ===\n* Depressants: [[Alcohol (drug)|Alcohol]], [[heroin]]\n* Stimulants: [[Cocaine]], [[methamphetamine]], [[nicotine]]\n\n=== Hard/soft drugs ===\n* Entactogens: [[MDMA]]\n* Dissociatives: [[ketamine]]\n* Stimulants: [[Caffeine]]\n* Psychedelics:[[LSD]]\n\n=== Soft drugs ===\n* Psychedelics: [, [[N,N-Dimethyltryptamine|DMT]], [[psilocybin]]\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:HarmCausedByDrugsTable.svg|alt=A chart showing relative drug harm.|A chart showing relative drug harm.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nutt|first=David|last2=King|first2=Leslie|last3=Phillips|first3=Lawrence|date=November 2010 |title=Drug harms in the UK: a multicriteria decision analysis|url=|journal=The Lancet|volume=376|issue=November 6, 2010|page=1561}}</ref>\nFile:Rational harm assessment of drugs radar plot.svg|A rational harm assessment of drugs<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Blakemore|first=Colin|last2=Saulsbury|first2=William|last3=King|first3=Leslie A.|last4=Nutt|first4=David|date=2007-03-24|title=Development of a rational scale to assess the harm of drugs of potential misuse|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(07)60464-4/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=369|issue=9566|pages=1047\u20131053|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(07)60464-4|issn=0140-6736|pmid=17382831}}</ref>\nFile:Drug danger and dependence.svg|alt=A chart showing dependence potential versus safety ratio.|An analysis of the dangers of drugs<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xpZhjBuDkuwC&pg=PA149|title=Drugs and Society: U.S. Public Policy|last=Fish|first=Jefferson M.|date=2006|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780742542457|language=en}}</ref>\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Designer drug]]\n* [[Drug policy of the Netherlands]]\n* [[Effective dose (pharmacology)]]\n* [[Effects of cannabis]]\n* [[Gateway drug theory]]\n* [[LD50]]\n* [[Responsible drug use]]\n* ''[[The Rhetoric of Drugs]]''\n\n== Sources ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Psychoactive substance use|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hard And Soft Drugs}}\n[[Category:Adverse effects of psychoactive drugs]]\n\n[[de:Weiche Drogen]]\n[[sv:L\u00e4tta droger]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Soft drug|meanings pertaining to the metabolism of drugs|retrometabolic drug design}}\n{{Disputed|date=November 2015}}\n[[File:Drug danger and dependence.svg|alt=|thumb|The diagram shows the dependence potential and the relation between active and lethal dose of some psychoactive substances]]\n'''Drug harmfulness''' is the degree to which a [[psychoactive drug]] is harmful to a user and is measured in various ways, such as by [[Substance use disorder|addictiveness]] and the potential for physical harm. More harmful drugs are called \"hard drugs\"<ref name=hardaz>{{cite book|title=The A-Z Encyclopedia of Alcohol and Drug Abuse|author=Thomas Nordegren|year=2002|isbn=1-58112-404-X|page=327|publisher=[[Brown Walker Press]]|location=Parkland, Fla.}}</ref>, and less harmful drugs are called \"soft drugs\".<ref name=softaz>{{cite book|title=The A-Z Encyclopedia of Alcohol and Drug Abuse|author=Thomas Nordegren|year=2002|isbn=1-58112-404-X|page=597|publisher=Brown Walker Press|location=Parkland, Fla.}}</ref> The term \"soft drug\" is considered controversial by its critics as it may imply that soft drugs cause no or insignificant harm.<ref name=softaz/>\n\n== Drug policy ==\nThe distinction between soft drugs and hard drugs is important in the [[drug policy of the Netherlands]], where [[Cannabis cultivation|cannabis production]], [[Cannabis coffee shops|retail]] and use come under official tolerance, subject to certain conditions. The Dutch [[Opium Law]] contains two lists of drugs, List I and List II, that are colloquially considered to be lists of hard and soft drugs, respectively. Other countries typically have more than two categories. For example, the [[United States]] has five schedules in the [[Controlled Substances Act]], ranging from one through five. The [[United Kingdom]] has three classes in the [[Misuse of Drugs Act 1971]]: A, B and C.\n\n== Hard and soft drugs ==\nAccording to the legal system of the Netherlands; selected soft drugs are tolerated legally while other hard drugs are illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.government.nl/topics/drugs/how-does-the-law-distinguish-between-soft-and-hard-drugs|title=How does the law distinguish between soft and hard drugs? - Drugs - Government.nl|first=Ministerie van Justitie en|last=Veiligheid|date=2 December 2013|website=www.government.nl}}</ref> Soft drugs can be tolerated in various ways whether it be total lack of regulation or some regulation, but still legal availability to the public.\n\n=== Hard drugs ===\n* Depressants: [[Alcohol (drug)|Alcohol]], [[heroin]]\n* Stimulants: [[Cocaine]], [[methamphetamine]], [[nicotine]]\n\n=== Hard/soft drugs ===\n* Entactogens: [[MDMA]]\n* Dissociatives: [[ketamine]]\n* Stimulants: [[Caffeine]]\n* Psychedelics:[[LSD]]\n\n=== Soft drugs ===\n* Psychedelics: [, [[N,N-Dimethyltryptamine|DMT]], [[psilocybin]]\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:HarmCausedByDrugsTable.svg|alt=A chart showing relative drug harm.|A chart showing relative drug harm.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nutt|first=David|last2=King|first2=Leslie|last3=Phillips|first3=Lawrence|date=November 2010 |title=Drug harms in the UK: a multicriteria decision analysis|url=|journal=The Lancet|volume=376|issue=November 6, 2010|page=1561}}</ref